   10 6 Enforcement ÿ Washington/Baltimore HIDTA Initiatives:17 * Violent
   Traffickers Initiative: This initiative, supervised by the DEA,
   investigates violent drug traffickers and violent drug trafficking
   organizations (DTOs) that have an impact on the Baltimore metropolitan
   area. ONDCP Clearinghouse 6 * Major Drug Traffickers Initiative: This
   Federal, State, and local unit, also supervised by the DEA, is designed
   to reduce drug trafficking in the Baltimore metropolitan area by
   focusing on major heroin and cocaine trafficking organizations and
   distributors. * Southern Maryland Crack and Gang Initiative: This
   multi-agency task force targets both violent and street-level/mid-level
   cocaine/crack organizations and youth gangs, operating in the Southern
   Maryland area. * Other Washington/Baltimore HIDTA Initiatives found in
   Maryland include the following: Charles County Joint Task Force; Prince
   George's and Montgomery County Initiative; Prince George's County
   Project Clean; and Mass Transportation Initiative. ÿ As of October
   1999, there were 18,252 full-time law enforcement employees in
   Maryland.18 Full-time Law Enforcement Employees, Maryland, 1999
   Officers Civilians Total M F M F Employees 12,292 1,840 1,493 2,627
   18,252 Courts ÿ As of August 8, 2001, there were 14 drug courts in
   Maryland that were either already in existence, recently implemented,
   or were being planned.19 * There are six drug courts in Maryland that
   have been in existence for over 2 years: ß 1 in Annapolis (Anne Arundel
   County) ß 3 in the City of Baltimore ß 1 in Edgewood (Harford County) ß
   1 in Easton (Talbot County) * One juvenile drug court has been recently
   implemented in Belair (Harford County). * There are also 7 additional
   drug courts being planned in Maryland: ß 2 in the City of Baltimore ß 1
   in Belair (Harford County) ß 2 in Ellicott City (Howard County) ß 1 in
   Rockville (Montgomery County) ß 1 in Upper Marlboro (Prince George's
   County) ÿ During FY00, 34.1% of the Federally sentenced offenders in
   Maryland had committed a drug offense. The majority of these offenses
   (45.7%) involved crack cocaine, while 27.2% involved powder cocaine,
   17.3% involved heroin, 7.5% involved marijuana, 1.7% involved
   methamphetamine, and 0.6% involved substances that do not fall into any
   of these categories.20 ÿ 96.5% of those convicted of drug trafficking
   were sentenced to a prison term.21 ÿ The average length of time a drug
   trafficking offender in Maryland would spend incarcerated was 128.8
   months. The national average for this same offense was 75.3 months.22
   ONDCP Clearinghouse 7 Corrections ÿ At yearend 2000, there were 23,538
   prisoners under the jurisdiction of State or Federal correctional
   authorities in Maryland.23 ÿ At the end of 2000, there were 83,852
   adults on probation in Maryland. This is a 3.2% increase in the
   probation population from the beginning of 2000.24 ÿ There were 14,143
   adults on parole in Maryland at the end of 2000. This is a 5.8%
   decrease in Maryland's parole population from the beginning of 2000.25
   Treatment ÿ During 1999, the number of substance abuse treatment
   admissions in Maryland reported to the U.S. Department of Health and
   Human Services totaled 56,479.26 ÿ 28.1% of those admitted were being
